types.name: Int
types.description: The `Int` scalar type represents non-fractional signed whole numeric values. Int can represent values between -(2^31) and 2^31 - 1.

types.name: Bond
types.description: Represents a lock on an operators bond, usually held by a keep the operator is collaterializing.

types.name: ID
types.description: The `ID` scalar type represents a unique identifier, often used to refetch an object or as key for a cache. The ID type appears in a JSON response as a String; however, it is not intended to be human-readable. When expected as an input type, any string (such as `"4"`) or integer (such as `4`) input value will be accepted as an ID.

types.name: String
types.description: The `String` scalar type represents textual data, represented as UTF-8 character sequences. The String type is most often used by GraphQL to represent free-form human-readable text.

fields.name: etcToBtcRatio
fields.description: The ratio of backing ETH to lot size. This allows you to sort by collateralization-ratio.

fields.name: stakedropInterval
fields.description: Which stakedrop interval this keep belongs to, if any.

fields.name: pubkeySubmissions
fields.description: The nodes which have submitted their pubkey.

fields.name: index
fields.description: An incrementing unique number for this deposit, starting at 1.

fields.name: createdAt
fields.description: Timestamp of when this deposit was created.

fields.name: closedAt
fields.description: Timestamp of when this deposit was closed, either due to redemption, liquidation, or setup failure.

fields.name: updatedAt
fields.description: Timestamp of the last state change of this deposit. Initialized to the same value as createdAt.

fields.name: redemptionStartedAt
fields.description: Timestamp of when the deposit redemption was requested, if any. This includes the start of liquidation due to undercollateralization. It is not reset if liquidation starts due to withdrawal failure. It does not reset in case of a fee increase.

fields.name: withdrawalRequestTimerStart
fields.description: Start point of the internal timer which begins with a redemption request. It is initially the same as `redemptionStartedAt` in case of manual redemption, but is reset if there is a fee increase. It is not set or reset when we enter liquidation.

fields.name: currentStateTimesOutAt
fields.description: The timeout after which the current state can be notified, if any. This does not include non-timeout actions that are time-locked, such as courtesy calls or liquidation auctions.

fields.name: creator
fields.description: The address which created the deposit initially. In contrast to the owner, this cannot change.

fields.name: lastActor
fields.description: The address which initiated the last action - initially the creator, then the redeemer.

fields.name: etcToBtcRatio
fields.description: The ratio of backing ETH to lot size. This allows you to sort by collateralization-ratio.

fields.name: filter_liquidationLikeState
fields.description: True if the deposit state is LIQUIDATED, LIQUIDATION_IN_PROGRESS, FRAUD_LIQUIDATION_IN_PROGRESS or COURTESY_CALL.

fields.name: filter_liquidationLikeOrSignerFailureState
fields.description: True if the deposit state is either liquidation like, or a signer setup failure.

types.name: Boolean
types.description: The `Boolean` scalar type represents `true` or `false`.

fields.name: liquidationInitiated
fields.description: The time the deposited entered LIQUIDATION_IN_PROGRESS state.

fields.name: courtesyCallInitiatedAt
fields.description: The last time a courtesy call was initiated, even if courtesy call state has been exited.

types.name: LiquidationCause
types.description: The reason why a deposit enter liquidation.

types.name: Lock
types.description: A lock on an operator stake. This is usually held by a deposit/keep contract.

types.name: Operator
types.description:
A node operator.

In Staking terms (https://docs.keep.network/random-beacon/staking/), there is an abstract role called the Staker,
representing owner, operator, beneficiary and authorizer. "Stakers are identified by their operator address", and
in our graph, through the Operator entity. Understand that in staking terms, only a single owner can delegate
their tokens to a particular owner, so the tokens staked always come from the samea address.

fields.name: stakedAt
fields.description: When this operator had a stake delegated to them. This is like a createdAt, and the operation also assigns the beneficiary/authorizer roles.

fields.name: totalTBTCRewards
fields.description: Rewards generated by this operator in TBTC, for any work.

fields.name: totalETHRewards
fields.description: Rewards generated by this operator in ETH, for any work.

fields.name: totalBeaconRewards
fields.description: ETH Rewards generated by this operator for random beacon work.

fields.name: attributableFaultCount
fields.description: How often this operator was involved in a fault, attributable to them.

fields.name: involvedInFaultCount
fields.description: How often this operator was involved in a fault, attributable to them.

fields.name: totalFaultCount
fields.description: How often this operator was involved in a fault, either attributable or not.

fields.name: stakeLockExpiryPoints
fields.description:
A list of timestamps, each representing the expiry date for a lock held on the stake.
We use this as a helper to be able to to calculate the maximum value, stakeLockExpiresAt.

fields.name: stakeLockExpiresAt
fields.description: The time when the last lock on the operator's stake expires. This can change when a lock is released early, or a new lock is added.

fields.name: _meta
fields.description: Access to subgraph metadata

fields.name: memberships
fields.description: A membership record for each unique member in the group.

fields.name: size
fields.description: The total number of slots. Since operators may appear multiple times, this is distinct from the unique number count of the group.

fields.name: uniqueMemberCount
fields.description: How many unique operators are in this group - the number of membership records.

fields.name: stakedropInterval
fields.description: Which stakedrop interval this groups belongs to, if any.

types.name: RandomBeaconGroupMembership
types.description: Represents the membership of an operator in a beacon group.

fields.name: count
fields.description: The same operator can fill multiple membership slots within a group.

fields.name: reward
fields.description: ETH reward amount (in wei) earned by this operator through membership in this group.

types.name: RedemptionFeeIncreasedEvent
types.description: If a Bitcoin fee increase is requested during the withdrawal process.

fields.name: reason
fields.description: The reason for the failure, based on which contract call caused the failure state to be entered.

types.name: StakedropInterval
types.description:
A one-month interval in the stakedrop reward program.

The intervals of the Beacon and ECDSA reward programs are not the same (there is about a 14 day difference).
However, the number of intervals are the same, and the programs are otherwise aligned conceptually, so there
is only one entity representing the intervals for both reward programs.

fields.name: number
fields.description: Nunber of the interval, with the first interval being 1.

fields.name: keeps
fields.description:
Keeps that fall into this interval, and are counted towards the allocated rewards. This includes terminated
keeps which are non-the-less not eligable for an reward.

fields.name: cause
fields.description: The cause of this deposit going into liquidation

types.name: StatsRecord
types.description: Exposes some global system statistics. Only a single record with the id "current" is available.

fields.name: depositCount
fields.description: Total number of deposits ever created, regardless of their current state.

fields.name: btcUnderDeposit
fields.description: The total amount of BTC currently deposited, measured from funding proof received to redemption proof received.

fields.name: btcInActiveDeposits
fields.description: The total amount of BTC currently deposited, measured from funding proof received to redemption requested

fields.name: totalGrantCount
fields.description: Total number of grants ever created, regardless of their current state.

fields.name: totalGrantIssued
fields.description: Total amount of grants issued.

types.name: StatusRecord
types.description: Exposes some global system status data. Only a single record with the id "current" is available.

fields.name: currentRequestedRelayEntry
fields.description: The currently requested RandomBeacon relay entry, if any. Only a single request can exist at a time.

types.name: User
types.description: An actor using the minting and redeeming facilities.

fields.name: numDepositsCreated
fields.description: The number of deposits the user initiated.

fields.name: numDepositsUnfunded
fields.description: The number of deposits the user initiated, then did not complete the funding process of. Excludes any deposits which failed due to signer issues.

fields.name: numDepositsRedeemed
fields.description: The number of deposits the user requested to be redeemed.

fields.name: numOwnDepositsRedeemed
fields.description: The number of deposits the user requested to be redeemed, where the deposit was also created by them.

types.name: _Meta_
types.description: The type for the top-level _meta field

fields.name: block
fields.description:
Information about a specific subgraph block. The hash of the block
will be null if the _meta field has a block constraint that asks for
a block number. It will be filled if the _meta field has no block constraint
and therefore asks for the latest  block

fields.name: deployment
fields.description: The deployment ID

types.name: __Schema
types.description: A GraphQL Schema defines the capabilities of a GraphQL server. It exposes all available types and directives on the server, as well as the entry points for query, mutation, and subscription operations.

fields.name: types
fields.description: A list of all types supported by this server.

fields.name: queryType
fields.description: The type that query operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: mutationType
fields.description: If this server supports mutation, the type that mutation operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: subscriptionType
fields.description: If this server support subscription, the type that subscription operations will be rooted at.

fields.name: directives
fields.description: A list of all directives supported by this server.

types.name: __Type
types.description:
The fundamental unit of any GraphQL Schema is the type. There are many kinds of types in GraphQL as represented by the `__TypeKind` enum.

Depending on the kind of a type, certain fields describe information about that type. Scalar types provide no information beyond a name, description and optional `specifiedByUrl`, while Enum types provide their values. Object and Interface types provide the fields they describe. Abstract types, Union and Interface, provide the Object types possible at runtime. List and NonNull types compose other types.

types.name: __TypeKind
types.description: An enum describing what kind of type a given `__Type` is.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a scalar.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an object. `fields` and `interfaces` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: INTERFACE
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an interface. `fields`, `interfaces`, and `possibleTypes` are valid fields.

enumValues.name: UNION
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a union. `possibleTypes` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: ENUM
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an enum. `enumValues` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: INPUT_OBJECT
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is an input object. `inputFields` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: LIST
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a list. `ofType` is a valid field.

enumValues.name: NON_NULL
enumValues.description: Indicates this type is a non-null. `ofType` is a valid field.

types.name: __Field
types.description: Object and Interface types are described by a list of Fields, each of which has a name, potentially a list of arguments, and a return type.

types.name: __InputValue
types.description: Arguments provided to Fields or Directives and the input fields of an InputObject are represented as Input Values which describe their type and optionally a default value.

fields.name: defaultValue
fields.description: A GraphQL-formatted string representing the default value for this input value.

types.name: __EnumValue
types.description: One possible value for a given Enum. Enum values are unique values, not a placeholder for a string or numeric value. However an Enum value is returned in a JSON response as a string.

types.name: __Directive
types.description:
A Directive provides a way to describe alternate runtime execution and type validation behavior in a GraphQL document.

In some cases, you need to provide options to alter GraphQL's execution behavior in ways field arguments will not suffice, such as conditionally including or skipping a field. Directives provide this by describing additional information to the executor.

types.name: __DirectiveLocation
types.description: A Directive can be adjacent to many parts of the GraphQL language, a __DirectiveLocation describes one such possible adjacencies.

enumValues.name: QUERY
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a query operation.

enumValues.name: MUTATION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a mutation operation.

enumValues.name: SUBSCRIPTION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a subscription operation.

enumValues.name: FIELD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a field.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment definition.

enumValues.name: FRAGMENT_SPREAD
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a fragment spread.

enumValues.name: INLINE_FRAGMENT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an inline fragment.

enumValues.name: VARIABLE_DEFINITION
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a variable definition.

enumValues.name: SCHEMA
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a schema definition.

enumValues.name: SCALAR
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to a scalar definition.

enumValues.name: OBJECT
enumValues.description: Location adjacent to an object type definition.

directives.name: skip
directives.description: Directs the executor to skip this field or fragment when the `if` argument is true.

args.name: if
args.description: Skipped when true.

directives.description: Directs the executor to include this field or fragment only when the `if` argument is true.

directives.name: deprecated
directives.description: Marks an element of a GraphQL schema as no longer supported.

args.name: reason
args.description: Explains why this element was deprecated, usually also including a suggestion for how to access supported similar data. Formatted using the Markdown syntax, as specified by [CommonMark](https://commonmark.org/).

directives.description: Exposes a URL that specifies the behaviour of this scalar.

args.name: url
